            <head>
              <title type="main">Teaching Blake</title>
            </head>
			<q> Before you go<lb/>
 a word further,<lb/>
 let me posit that<lb/>
 teaching
                            Blake<lb/>
 requires a kind of<lb/>
 rigor<lb/>
 you may<lb/>
 want to
                            avoid,<lb/>
<lb/>
 that is, unless<lb/>
 you’ve learned<lb/>
 enough
                            detachment<lb/>
 from day-long conversations,<lb/>
 matching
                            silences<lb/>
<lb/>
 —in rooms of<lb/>
 Virginia, Libya,<lb/>
 and
                            Japan<lb/>
 where drapes<lb/>
 match<lb/>
 sofas and<lb/>
 beds,<lb/>
 where
                            paintings<lb/>
 match<lb/>
 neither—<lb/>
<lb/>
 to suggest<lb/>
 with
                            restraint,<lb/>
 of course,<lb/>
<lb/>
 that eleven o’clock<lb/>
                            efforts, even<lb/>
 lifting a coffee mug,<lb/>
 a fax, a receiver,<lb/>
 a
                            finger, are<lb/>
 bivalved<lb/>
 marriages<lb/>
 of heaven<lb/>
 and
                            hell,<lb/>
 acidic mysteries of<lb/>
 some concern. </q>
